As usual, I started by creating a directory on my local machine and cloning the Bandit repository into it.

The README.md file explained that I needed to create a file named key.txt containing the text May I come in? and commit it to the master branch.

At first, I couldn't add the file because the repository included a hidden .gitignore file that ignored all .txt files. To get around this, I used the -f option with git add to force Git to stage the file despite the ignore rule.

Once the file was committed, I pushed the changes to the remote master branch using:

---------------------------------------
git push -u origin master
---------------------------------------

The -u option sets the upstream relationship between the local and remote branches, so future git push and git pull commands can be used without specifying the remote or branch each time. 
origin is simply the default name of the remote repository—it isn't a reserved keyword and can be renamed if needed. master refers to the local branch being pushed.

